Finish rollout: ["<｜begin▁of▁sentence｜><｜User｜>Give me the answer of the following equation: 664 * 519 = <｜Assistant｜><think>\nOkay, so I need to figure out the multiplication of 664 and 519. Hmm, let me think of the best way to approach this without a calculator because actually calculating it in my head would be tricky. Maybe I can break it down into smaller parts or use the distributive property.\n\nFirst, I can rewrite 519 as 500 + 19. That might make the multiplication easier. So, the equation becomes 664 multiplied by 500 plus 664 multiplied by 19. Let me write that down: 664*519 = 664*(500+19) = 664*500 + 664*19.\n\nAlright, starting with 664*500. Well, multiplying by 500 is the same as multiplying by 5 and then adding two zeros. Let's compute 664*5 first. 664*5: let's break it down further. 600*5 is 3000, and 64*5 is 320. So 3000 + 320 = 3320. Then add the two zeros: 3320 followed by two zeros is 332000. Wait, wait no, 664*500 is actually 664 * 5 * 100, which is 3320*100=332,000. Yes, correct. Right.\n\nNow the next part is 664*19. Hmm, okay, 19 is 20 minus 1, so maybe I'll use distributive there too. Let me try that. 664*19 = 664*(20 - 1) = 664*20 - 664*1.\n\n664*20: well that's 664*2*10 which is 1328*10=13280.\n\nSo subtract 664*1 which is 664 from that. 13280 - 664. Let me calculate 13280 - 600 is 12680, minus 64 is 12616. So 664*19=12616.\n\nSo now, adding the two parts: 664*500=332,000 and 664*19=12,616? Wait wait, wait let's verify the numbers. Wait, no, earlier I said 19 was broken into 20 -1, so 664*20=13,280 and 664*1=664, so 13,280 minus 664 is 12,616. So yes, 12,616.\n\nSo total is 332,000 +12,616. Let's add those together. 332,000 + 12,616. That is 344,616.\n\nWait, let me check that addition step by step:\n\n332,000 +12,000 is 344,000. Then add the remaining 616: 344,000 + 616=344,616. Yeah, so 332,000 + 12,616 =344,616.\n\nTherefore the product is 344,616.\n\nWait but let me verify this another way using another method to avoid errors.\n\nAlternatively, I can compute 664 * 519 directly.\n\n519 is 500 +19. So 664 * 519 = 664*500 + 664*19.\n\nWait which is exactly what I did earlier.\n\nLet me verify:\n\nCalculate 664*500: As 664*5=3320, then *100 is 332,000. Correct.\n\n664*19, let me use another method just to double check.\n\nMultiplying 664 by 19:\n\nI can compute 664*10=6640\n\n664*9= let's calculate 664*9: 600*9=5400, 64*9=576; Sum is 5400+576=5976.\n\nThen 664*19= 664*10 +664*9 = 6640 +5976= let's compute 6640 +5976.\n\nAdding 6640 + 5976:\n\n6640 + 5976:\n\nAdding units:\n\n6640 +5976:\n6000 +5900 = 11900? Wait better compute step by step.\n\n6640 + 5976:\n\nStart:\n\n6640 + 5000= 11640,\n\n11640 + 976 = 12616.\n\nSo 12616. Same result. Then 664*19 is indeed 12,616. Then total 332,000 +12,616= 344,616.\n\nWait, 332,000 +12,616.\n\n332,000 +12,000 is 344,000.\n\n344,000 +616 is 344,616. Yep.\n\nNow another method: Let me verify using another way to make sure.\n\nCompute 664 * 519.\n\nLet me break down 519 as 500 + 19 as before or perhaps 500 is e.g. 500 and add 19.\n\nBut anyway, 664*519:\n\nCompute 664*519.\n\nMultiply 519*664.\n\nCompute 664*500=332,000\n\n664*19=12,616, so sum 332,000 + 12,616=344,616.\n\nLet me confirm once.\n\nCompute 664 * 519:\n\nI can compute 519*(600 + 64). Wait maybe an alternative breakdown.\n\nWait perhaps multiply 519 by 664:\n\nCompute 500*664=332,000.\n\n19*664:\n\nCompute 10*664 = 6,640\n\n9*664: Let's see, 600*9=5,400? Wait wait 9*600 is 5400, but wait 19 is 10+9.\n\nWait, wait 19*664: (20 -1)*664= 13,280 -664= 12,616.\n\nWhich brings back to previous computation: 500*664=332,000 and 19*664= 12,616; together 332,000+12,616=344,616.\n\nSame result. Therefore, confident the product is 344,616.\n\nAlternatively, let's verify using another method:\n\nUse standard multiplication:\n\n664\nx519\n________\n\nLet me set it up:\n\nMultiply 664 by 9:\n\n664 * 9: Let's calculate:\n\n600*9=5400; 64*9=576; Total 5400 + 576=5976.\n\nThen, multiply 664 by 1 (tens place):\n\n664*1=664, shifted one position left: 6640\n\nMultiply 664 by 5 (hundreds place):\n\n664 * 5= Let's see:\n\n600*5=3000\n64*5=320; total=3320\nShift two positions: 3320*100=332,000.\n\nNow sum all together:\n\nFirst digit multiplication:\n\nUnits place (units digit): 5976\n\nTens place: 6640 (shifted once).\nHundreds place: 332000 shifted twice. But let me see the addition step:\n\nWait standard multiplication layout:\n\n   664\nx519\nMultiply 664 * 519\n\nBreakdown:\n\nMultiply by units digit 9: 664 *9=5976\n\nMultiply"], label: None, reward: {'reward': -1.0, 'accuracy': 0, 'format_score': 0}
