igit or more.\n\nLet me consider it step by step:\n\nWe have N = 117973\n\nDivisor D=158\n\nStart by taking the first three digits of N: 117.\n\n158 > 117, can't go, take first four digits:1179.\n\nCompute 1179 ÷ 158:\n\n158*7=1106,\n\n1179 -1106=73\n\nSo quotient so far is 7, remainder 73\n\nBring down the next digit, which is7: making it 737.\n\nNow divide 737 by158:\n\n158*4=632\n\n158*5=790 too big. So 4*158=632.\n\nSubtract: 737 -632=105.\n\nBring down next digit 3: making it 1053.\n\nDivide 1053 by 158:\n\n158*6=948\n\n1053 -948=105.\n\nBring down nothing as we are at last digit.\n\nSo altogether quotient so far is 7, 4, 6 with last partial:\n\nWait let me compile:\n\nFirst division step with 1179 ÷158 was:\n\n7, remainder 73\n\nBring down 7: 737 ÷158 is 4, remainder105\n\nBring down next digit3: making 1053÷158:\n\n6*158 =948, remainder105\n\nSo the total quotient digits are 746, with final remainder?\n\nWait let's see:\n\nSo building the quotient:\n\nFirst digit was 7 (thousands place), then 4 (hundreds), then 6 (tens)?\n\nWait let me pause.\n\nLet me redo this using long division properly step-by-step:\n\nDivisor: 158\n\nDividend: 117973.\n\nStep 1:\n\n117973 divided by 158:\n\n158 into 117,973\n\nFirst, how many times does 158 go into 1179 (first four digits?) Wait perhaps tabular form would be better.\n\nWait perhaps write dividend digits:\n\nDividend: 1 1 7 9 7 3\n\nWait let's go step by step:\n\n- 158 into 11 and the next is 117, (\nWait maybe better process:\n\n1. How many times does 158 go into 117? 0, since 117 is less than158.\n\nSo write0 and consider 1179. 158 goes into 1179 how many times?\n\nCalculate 158*7=1106, 158*8=1264. 1179-1106=73.\n\nFirst quotient digit:7.\n\nSubtract, remainder:73\n\nBring down the 7: making it 737\n\n"], label: None, reward: {'reward': -1.0, 'accuracy': 0, 'format_score': 0}
